Comment: Dear Ms. Perdue, You must receive hundreds of emails a day. I have yet one more to add to your inbox. I have a great concern with the cut backs in mental health. The decision to eliminate group homes and/or funding for these services is an extreme disservice to our state and the families within that are in great need of them. This topic is very personal to me as my stepson is mentally retarded and has a great deal of 24-7 medical needs that cannot be provided at home. Simply stated, he needs round-the-clock care and constant supervision. He was born with a rare disorder, Nonketotic Hyperglycinemia (NKH), which is an inadequate supply of an enzyme necessary to break down glycine in the body. The abnormally high levels of glycine is toxic and has left him severely & profoundly mentally-retarded, autistic, non-verbal, aggressive, seizures... He is treated with life sustaining medications daily. In conjunction with his medical needs, we‚Äôve had a very long, turbulent road over the past year with his increasingly aggressive behavior. I can‚Äôt express to you how difficult it is to restrain this 14 year-old child, multiple times a day. I have literally walked away from him bitten, bruised and bleeding, many times. Being physically and emotionally drained, dealing with this day after day, we became desperate. We took him to the local emergency department and simply told them that we cannot handle him anymore. After three days of being cooped up in a rubber room in the ED and one week on the peds floor, he was temporarily placed into the Murdoch Center in Butner. After nearly a two month stay there, he was transferred to a local group home (Unity Residential Services, Willow Springs) last July. To sum up a really long story, he is NOW in an environment where he is thriving because of the 24-7 care, attention and routine that he desperately needs. I basically summarized some of the things we‚Äôve had to endure in recent years with him. I‚Äôm also going to copy and 