eing attacked by Robert. We have pictures from several recent incidents where Robert has badly bruised, bitten, and scratched us. The physicians at UNC Hospitals also have photos that were taken of us with marks and bruising, as well as several employees that were injured during his short stay there (including a broken wrist suffered by a nurse). Robert is no stranger to the PATH program. He was admitted for a 90 day respite period in 2006. For some time following that period, Robert exhibited improvements in behavior, self-help skills, and communication. This definitively demonstrated the success of the PATH program. However, in the period between 2006 and now, Robert‚Äôs behavior has degenerated steadily and severely. These extreme changes seem to coincide with the onset of puberty. We have tried many other avenues, including searching for specialized programs, exploring additional behavior medications, and placement in group homes (which have declined Robert based on the severity of his behaviors). Since the PATH program was so successful, we considered this to be the best option for Robert. Our feelings were correct, because while in PATH for the last 30 days Robert‚Äôs aggressive behavior has been significantly curbed. He is a completely different child. This, again, demonstrates the success of the PATH program in proving the type of environment and structure that Robert can thrive in. Any decision made on the basis of Robert‚Äôs behavior while currently in the PATH program are based on a gross misconception of the severity and intensity of his aggressive behaviors. We believe that a grave mistake was made by the admission board. Therefore, based on these and the following issues, we formally appeal the admission decision: -Robert has severe behavioral challenges that impede his safety and those around him. These include but are not limited to: closed fist hitting, open fist hitting, clawing, biting, hair pulling, scratching, throwing objects, running off, dropping ‚Äúdead weight‚Äù and aggressively attacking when attempting to move him, getting out of seat belt and attacking driver in moving car. -His behaviors are continuous and directly affect his ability to learn important daily life skills. This is exemplified by the refusal of therapists to work with him based on his aggressive behavior (OT, PT, rehab tech, etc.) -His behaviors are intense and cause injury w/ individuals who are not physically able to restrain him (brothers, grandparents, teachers, workers, mother, etc.) -He has been declined from several group home placements due to his behavioral needs. I urge you to reconsider Roberts application so that he has the time to learn goals in an environment that is able to help control old and teach new appropriate behaviors to him. Thank you, Lori and Michael Wyde

